			Story 1 — From Aarong Forest to Sunveil Market Town

	Bromir Ironfist often begins this tale with a wry smile, his voice rich with pride and just a hint of resentment.

*"I wasn’t always here, mind you. No, my hands first shaped the walls of a city far grander than any humble settlement on this island. I come from the dwarves of Aarong Forest, deep in the Outland Territories. There lies the Ancient City of Sankis, a marvel that had seen centuries crumble and kings fall, yet I, Bromir Ironfist, was entrusted with restoring it. Fifty subordinates at my command, men and dwarves who learned quickly the price of slacking when I was at the helm. I gave them little rest, little comfort, for perfection was demanded, and perfection is what I delivered."*

	He pauses, leaning on a nearby anvil, eyes glinting as though the flames of memory dance behind them.

*"The reconstruction was no mere task; it was a symphony of stone, steel, and iron. Every wall, every rampart, every forged gate had to endure the memories of battles past and the storms yet to come. I worked with the greatest architects of the era, dwarves and humans alike, whose names will be etched in history long after my beard turns white. And heroes — yes, heroes of the Second Great War — they walked among us, observing, offering counsel, learning from those of us who wielded hammers instead of swords."*

	Bromir chuckles, shaking his head.

*"And then, after the great work was done — when the city stood taller, stronger, and prouder than ever — they sent me here. To this island. Sunveil Market Town. For what, you ask? To assist hunters who believe themselves warriors merely because they can swing a sword. Honor? Perhaps. From my perspective, a downgrade, yes. They sent me here because my skill is undeniable, and yet, to them, I am a mere assistant. I am told to prepare the hunters, to help them ascend into the Tomb of Great Crusaders. Ha! If they only knew the sweat, the fire, the hours, the knowledge I poured into Sankis’ walls, they might understand why I grumble."*

	He huffs, dusting ash from his apron, as though the ghosts of Sankis still cling to his work.

*"But I do it. I came here, I work here, and I craft here. Every wall, every weapon forged, every piece of armor I shape carries the weight of Sankis. I tell the apprentices of what it means to be perfect. I tell the hunters of precision, of balance, of patience. And one day, when they understand even a fraction of what I have learned, I will smile, perhaps then I will feel my work has echoed beyond the stones of Sankis and into the steel of Sunveil."*

	He rests his hands on the forge and glances at the furnaces glowing warmly.

*"Ah, but don’t let them think I have forgotten. I am still Bromir Ironfist of Aarong Forest. Sankis is in my heart, my legacy. Here, I build new legends, one hammer strike at a time, hoping some day my apprentices may wield the knowledge I earned at the cost of sweat and years."*

